Bryan's maxent analytical continuation algorithm

Usage:
  bryan -w <frequencies> [options] [(-m <file> | -M <m1,m2> ...)] <datafile>

Options:
  -w --frequencies=<#omega>        Number of real frequency points
  -W --frequencyrange=<omega_max>  Frequncy range. Symmetric for -s F, positive for -s X. Ignored if modelfile is provided [default: 20.0]
  -S --statistics=<(F|X)>          Fermionic or real bosonic continuation [default: F]
  -m --modelfile=<file>            Provide a default model
  -M --moments=<m1,m2>             Moment list for default model. m0 is fixed to 1.0
  -s --sigma=<sigma>               Standard deviation of the input data. If not provided, it is assumed to be an additional column in the input data file
  -o --outfile=<file>              Result is written to <file> instead of <datafile>_dos.dat
  -p --modelnorm=<norm>            Intended norm of the model. Expert only [default: 1.0]
  -g --gnuplot                     Enable live gnuplot view of algorithm (recommended)
  -h --help                        Show this message and exit

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Columns in datafile (-S F only)
tau Gtau1 sigma1 Gtau2 sigma2 Gtau3 sigma3...

Columns in datafile (-S X only)
omega_n [ReW(i omega_n)] ImW(i omega_n)

Call:
> ./bryan.py -h

for infos.

For the enclosed test-file, use e.g.
> ./bryan.py -S X -s 0.01 -w 800 -W 100 -m Wmodel.dat W.dat -g
or
> ./bryan.py -w 700 -W 20 -M 1.5,1.2 Gtau.dat -g

however the algorithm handles gracefully much larger meshes, both in omega and in tau

The output is written to "dos.dat", possibly overwriting older results.

A helpful on-the-fly visualization of the algorithm is available if gnuplot-python is installed and -g is given

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

WARNING!!!
I wrote this tool to be able to cope with the large number of 
time-slices that comes along with modern CT-QMC algorithms. Other than 
that, it's more or less a word-by-word implementation of Bryan's 
algorithm (Eur. Biophys. J 18 (1990) ).
I tested against trivial cases and other codes and also got positive
feedback from other users, of course I can nevertheless not give any 
guarantee for the correctness of the code!
